<div id="review_3131123723" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3131123723" />
    <a title="Matt (TeamRedmon)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3464026-matt-teamredmon"><img alt="Matt (TeamRedmon)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1562023660p2/3464026.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3131123723?book_show_action=true">Jan 13, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Matt (TeamRedmon)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Matt (TeamRedmon)" href="/user/show/3464026-matt-teamredmon">Matt (TeamRedmon)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3131123723" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18221286903904014727">I ended up liking this one but there were times at the beginning that I wanted to DNF. The story starts off extremely slowly with lots of character development on the two main characters Boris Dragosani and Harry Keogh. As a math teacher, I enjoyed the multiple chapters dedicated to Harry&apos;s performance in math class at school but if I wasn&apos;t a math nerd, I&apos;d have given up then. But once the story got going...eventually, I really enjoyed myself. There are references to Bram Stoker&apos;s Dracula and t</span>
  <span id="freeText18221286903904014727" style="display:none">I ended up liking this one but there were times at the beginning that I wanted to DNF. The story starts off extremely slowly with lots of character development on the two main characters Boris Dragosani and Harry Keogh. As a math teacher, I enjoyed the multiple chapters dedicated to Harry's performance in math class at school but if I wasn't a math nerd, I'd have given up then. But once the story got going...eventually, I really enjoyed myself. There are references to Bram Stoker's Dracula and the characters know about the vampire myth which led to some interesting exchanges when the vampire actually shows up. <br /><br />The characters of Dragosani and Keogh are two sides of the same coin, Keogh is a Necroscope (can hear the thoughts of the dead) and Dragosani is a Necromancer (can get information from the dead by fondling their internal organs). Necroscope is primarily their story. While Lumley does a wonderful and original job handling the myth of the vampire, this book is mostly about those two men and their journey towards inevitable confrontation with each other. The journey to that ultimate battle is brutal, interesting, and quite weird and Harry Keogh is one of my new favorite characters. I'm quite excited to discover a new, and quite extensive, series that revolve around the Necroscope. I'll definitely be reading those eventually.<br /><br />I enjoyed this quite a bit and recommend it to anyone that is looking for an original take on vampires. Just be sure to stick with it through the first 100-150 pages, it's worth it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18221286903904014727" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
